{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.4,0.16,0.03,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107238"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8416"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89697"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39847"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107238"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine diabetes review. She has had type 2 diabetes mellitus for eight years, treated with metformin and empagliflozin. Her most recent glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) is 9.2%. She reports no visual symptoms. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Fundoscopy reveals multiple small red dots and yellow-white deposits scattered throughout the retina. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the earliest detectable sign of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hard exudates","Microaneurysms","Dot haemorrhages","Venous beading","Cotton wool spots"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has background (non-proliferative) diabetic retinopathy. The fundoscopic findings show characteristic features including microaneurysms (small red dots) and hard exudates (yellow-white deposits).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroaneurysms\u003C/strong\u003E are the earliest clinically detectable sign of diabetic retinopathy. They appear as tiny, round, red dots on fundoscopy and represent small outpouchings of weakened capillary walls. They are often the only visible abnormality in mild diabetic retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHard exudates\u003C/strong\u003E appear later in the disease process. They are yellow-white deposits of lipid and protein that have leaked from damaged blood vessels. While they are a characteristic feature of diabetic retinopathy, they are not the earliest sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDot haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E occur when microaneurysms rupture or when there is bleeding from damaged capillaries. They appear similar to microaneurysms but are typically larger and occur after microaneurysms have developed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECotton wool spots\u003C/strong\u003E represent areas of retinal ischaemia and appear as fluffy white lesions. They indicate more severe non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy and appear later in the disease course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous beading\u003C/strong\u003E is a sign of severe non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy where retinal veins develop irregular dilated segments. It is a late finding that indicates severe retinal ischaemia and a high risk of progression to proliferative retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Microaneurysms are the earliest detectable sign of diabetic retinopathy on fundoscopy.","Hard exudates and dot/blot haemorrhages are characteristic features of non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy."],"references":["Shukla UV, Tripathy K. Diabetic Retinopathy In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560805/","Royal Australian College of General Practitioner Management of Type 2 Diabetes Guidelines. Diabetes-related eye disease [Internet]. Royal Australian College of General Practitioners Clinical Guidelines. 2025. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/management-of-type-2-diabetes/complications/diabetes-related-eye-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89697"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89697"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T19:42:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T19:42:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107238"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name